## Interview Questions & Answers

**Q1. What is the CAP Theorem?**
The CAP theorem states that in a distributed system, you can only simultaneously guarantee two out of three properties: Consistency (all nodes see the same, most recent data), Availability (every request gets a response, even if not the most recent data), and Partition Tolerance (the system continues to function despite communication breakdowns between nodes).

**Q2. Explain Consistency, Availability, and Partition Tolerance in your own words.**
Consistency means every read returns the most up-to-date write, regardless of which node handles the request. Availability means every request receives some response (success or failure of the operation, but the system itself responds), even if some nodes are down. Partition Tolerance means the system keeps functioning correctly even when network communication between nodes is disrupted or delayed.

**Q3. Why is Partition Tolerance often considered "non-negotiable" in real distributed systems?**
Because network partitions (dropped connections, delayed messages, hardware/network failures) are essentially inevitable in any real-world distributed system operating across multiple nodes or data centers. Since you can't fully prevent partitions from happening, a truly distributed system must be designed to tolerate them — making the practical choice mostly between Consistency and Availability specifically during a partition event.

**Q4. What is a CP database? Give an example and a use case.**
A CP database prioritizes Consistency and Partition Tolerance over Availability — during a network partition, it may take some nodes offline (become unavailable) rather than risk serving stale/inconsistent data. MongoDB is an example; it's well-suited for use cases like banking systems, where returning incorrect/outdated data is far worse than temporary unavailability.

**Q5. What is an AP database? Give an example and a use case.**
An AP database prioritizes Availability and Partition Tolerance over strict Consistency — during a partition, all nodes remain available and responsive, but some might serve slightly stale data until the partition resolves and nodes re-sync (eventual consistency). Apache Cassandra is an example; it's well-suited for use cases like social media platforms (e.g., Facebook), where staying "always on" matters more than every user seeing perfectly up-to-date data instantly.

**Q6. Why are CA databases considered impractical for real distributed systems?**
CA databases guarantee Consistency and Availability but not Partition Tolerance — meaning they assume network partitions simply won't happen. Since partitions are essentially unavoidable in any genuinely distributed, multi-node system over time, a database that can't handle partitions gracefully isn't a realistic choice for large-scale distributed deployments; CA setups are really only viable for non-partitioned/single-node style deployments.

**Q7. How does MongoDB implement its CP behavior internally?**
MongoDB structures each replica set so that there is only ONE primary node that accepts all write requests at a given time; secondary nodes replicate data from the primary. If the primary becomes unreachable (e.g., during a network partition), the system elects a new primary from the secondaries rather than allowing multiple nodes to accept conflicting writes — sacrificing availability briefly (while election happens) to preserve consistency.

**Q8. How does Cassandra achieve high availability with no primary node?**
Cassandra uses a masterless (leaderless) architecture where every node can accept both read and write requests — there's no single primary node that could become a bottleneck or single point of failure. During a partition, all nodes remain available and can independently accept writes; once the partition resolves, Cassandra uses eventual consistency mechanisms to reconcile and synchronize any conflicting/stale data across nodes.

**Q9. What does "eventual consistency" mean, and which CAP category typically relies on it?**
Eventual consistency means that if no new updates are made, all replicas/nodes will eventually converge to the same, consistent value over time — but at any given moment (especially right after a write or during a partition), different nodes might temporarily return different (stale) data. AP databases (like Cassandra, DynamoDB) typically rely on eventual consistency, since they prioritize availability over strict/immediate consistency.

**Q10. Why would a banking application choose a CP database over an AP database?**
Because in banking, serving incorrect or stale data (e.g., showing an outdated account balance that allows an overdraft, or double-processing a transaction) can have serious real-world financial and legal consequences. A CP database ensures that if consistency can't be guaranteed during a partition (e.g., due to nodes being out of sync), the system will restrict availability on the affected nodes rather than risk serving incorrect data — prioritizing correctness over uptime.

**Q11. Why would a social media application like Facebook choose an AP database over a CP database?**
Because for a social media platform, occasionally showing a slightly outdated like-count, comment, or post (a minor consistency issue) is a far more acceptable trade-off than the app becoming unavailable/unresponsive to users. AP databases ensure the app stays "always on" and responsive, even during network issues, accepting that some data might briefly be stale until it eventually syncs.

**Q12. What is the PACELC theorem, and how does it extend CAP?**
PACELC extends CAP by addressing what happens even when there's NO partition: "if there is a Partition, trade off Availability vs Consistency; Else, trade off Latency vs Consistency." This fills a gap in CAP theorem's scope — CAP only discusses trade-offs during a partition event, but PACELC recognizes that distributed systems always face a trade-off between response speed (Latency) and data Consistency, even during normal (non-partitioned) operation.
